The individual's immediate social and relational environment can have a substantial impact on their educational outcomes. Studies have demonstrated that factors such as family structure, poverty, and community resources can significantly influence the educational experiences and outcomes of a person. Research has indicated, for instance, that children from single-parent households are more likely to have poorer scholastic success and graduation rates than children from two-parent households. This may be due to a number of circumstances, including a lack of emotional and financial support from a second parent and a dearth of role models with advanced degrees. Additionally, poverty might negatively affect educational outcomes. Children from low-income households are more likely to attend schools with fewer resources and less-experienced teachers, which can result in poorer academic performance. In addition, they may lack access to technology, extracurricular activities, and educational materials, all of which are necessary for a quality education. In addition, the degree of education and income of a person's parents might influence their educational success. Children of parents with higher levels of education and money are more likely to have positive educational experiences and results, in part because they have greater access to educational resources and opportunities. The individual's neighbourhood and area might also have an impact on their educational success. Children residing in regions with a high crime rate and restricted access to community facilities, such as libraries and parks, may have fewer educational chances and face more educational obstacles. The immediate social and relational milieu in which a person grows up can have a substantial effect on their educational success. Factors such as family structure, poverty, and community resources can influence an individual's educational experiences and opportunities, as well as their academic performance. 